# Cyrius — Agent Guides
# Read-this-first rules for AI agents writing or modifying Cyrius code.
# Plus tcyr/test conventions and known anti-patterns.
# 3 entries.

[[entries]]
name = "cyrius_for_agents"
description = "Read-this-first rules for agents writing or modifying Cyrius code. Every item below caused a real mistake by an agent at least once."
category = "cyrius"
---
This entry is the consolidated short list of "things an agent
must know before writing Cyrius code." Each rule cites the
slot or memory entry where an agent (often me) made the
mistake first.

== TOP-LEVEL CODE IS THE PROGRAM ENTRY POINT ==

Cyrius has NO auto `main()` call. The program is whatever
top-level statements appear at file scope, executed in
order. A `fn main() { ... }` definition is just a function;
nothing calls it unless you do.

    # WRONG — main() never runs:
    fn main() {
        syscall(60, 42);
        return 0;
    }

    # RIGHT — top-level statement is the entry:
    var rc = main();
    syscall(60, rc);

    # OR — skip the wrapper:
    syscall(60, 42);

== `.tcyr` TESTS NEED EXPLICIT EXIT ==

`assert_summary()` returns the FAILURE count, not 0/non-0
status. Tests must explicitly use it as the exit code:

    # WRONG — exit code is the failure count, but the CI
    # runner does `if [ "$ec" -ne 0 ]; then FAIL; fi`,
    # so a passing test (assert_summary returns the pass
    # count) is reported as FAIL by CI:
    assert_summary();

    # ALSO WRONG — same problem from a different angle:
    return assert_summary();

    # RIGHT — exit 0 on full pass, non-zero on failure:
    var r = assert_summary();
    syscall(60, r);

== MISSING `lib/foo.cyr` INCLUDE = UD2 SIGILL ==

Cyrius's --strict mode escalates undefined-fn references
to errors, but the default mode warns then patches the
call site to `0F 0B 0F 0B 90` (`ud2; ud2; nop`) so the
crash is loud SIGILL (exit 132) instead of silent jump
into trampoline. So if you see exit 132 from a test or
program, add the missing `include "lib/X.cyr"`.

Common ones agents miss:
- `lib/string.cyr` — provides `streq`, `strlen`, `memcpy`,
  `memset`, `memeq`. Without it, anything that calls these
  SIGILLs.
- `lib/syscalls.cyr` — provides `SYS_*` constants and the
  `syscall` builtin. (Actually `syscall` is intrinsic, but
  the constants come from this file.)
- `lib/fdlopen.cyr` — required by `lib/tls.cyr` (PP cap
  blocks auto-include). Tests using TLS must include
  fdlopen first.
- `lib/sha1.cyr`, `lib/keccak.cyr`, `lib/ct.cyr` — required
  by sigil consumers.

The error message at compile time names every undef fn —
read it.

== NO `var x` REDECL IN SAME SCOPE ==

`var x = 1; var x = 2;` is a parse error. Use plain
reassignment: `var x = 1; x = 2;`. Or open a new scope
with `{ var x = 2; }` if you want shadowing.

== MIXED `&&` / `||` REQUIRES PARENS ==

`a > 0 && b > 0 || c > 0` fails to parse — no
precedence-based disambiguation. Always parenthesize:
`a > 0 && (b > 0 || c > 0)` or `(a > 0 && b > 0) || c > 0`.

== `var buf[N]` IS BYTES, NOT i64 SLOTS ==

`var buf[8]` is 8 bytes (1 i64 slot). For an N-element
i64 array, write `var buf[N * 8]`. Easy mistake.

== STRINGS ARE C-STRINGS BY DEFAULT ==

`"hello"` is a 6-byte buffer (5 chars + null terminator).
Functions like `strlen` give the un-null-counted length.
For a heap-allocated counted string with O(1) length, use
`Str` from `lib/string.cyr` (`var s = str_from("hello");`).

== `\n` IS ONE BYTE ==

When passing a string literal length to `syscall(SYS_WRITE,
1, "hello\n", N)`, count `\n` as 1 byte. Common mistake:
counting `\n` as 2 bytes (`\` + `n`).

    # CORRECT byte counts:
    "hello\n"           is  6 bytes
    "got\nback\n"       is  9 bytes
    "exit: "            is  6 bytes

== SYSCALL ARITY WARNINGS ARE REAL ==

`syscall(SYS_WRITE, 1, msg, len)` takes 4 args. If you write
3 or 5, cyrius warns at compile time but emits anyway. The
warning means the wrong number of registers got loaded —
the syscall will see the WRONG args.

If you see `warning:lib/syscalls_x86_64_linux.cyr:N: syscall
arity mismatch` in your build output, fix the syscall arity
at the call site shown in the diagnostic.

== CYRIUS `/` AND `%` ARE SIGNED ==

The `/` operator lowers to `idiv`, not `div`. For unsigned
operations where the high bit matters (cryptographic
mulmod, hash mixing, high-entropy counters), use the stdlib's
`u64_mulmod` / `u64_powmod` / `u128_divmod` from
`lib/u128.cyr` — they handle unsigned semantics internally.

== FUNCTION ORDERING IS RELAXED ==

You can reference a function before its definition. The
compiler does a pre-scan pass to register all fn names +
sigs. Mutual recursion just works.

== INLINE ASM OFFSETS ARE FRAGILE ==

`asm { ... }` blocks that hardcode `[rbp-N]` offsets to
read locals depend on:
- The fn's param count (each param after rdi takes a slot)
- The fn's local index (var declaration order)
- Whether `#regalloc` is active (shifts locals -8 per saved reg)

`fncall0..fncall8` in `lib/fnptr.cyr` are the canonical
examples. The compiler auto-skips regalloc for fns with
`asm` bodies; you don't need to manually opt out, but you
also can't expect inline asm to combine cleanly with
regalloc within the same fn.

== `#ifdef` IS PREPROCESSOR-ONLY, NO RUNTIME QUERY ==

`CYRIUS_ARCH_X86` and `CYRIUS_ARCH_AARCH64` are set during
preprocessing, NOT at runtime. You CAN'T do
`if (CYRIUS_ARCH_X86) { ... }` — that's a runtime ident
lookup that fails. Use `#ifdef CYRIUS_ARCH_X86 ...
#endif` instead.

== INCLUDES ARE INCLUDE-ONCE BY FILENAME ==

`include "lib/foo.cyr"` will be inlined at most once per
compilation unit, even if multiple files include it. The
preprocessor tracks already-included filenames.

Caveat: relative paths and absolute paths to the same file
ARE different from the include-once perspective. Stick to
the conventional `include "lib/foo.cyr"` shape and you're
fine.

== HEAP REGIONS ARE FIXED (NOT MMAP'D ON DEMAND) ==

cycc reserves a multi-MB heap at brk. Every region
(preprocess_out, codebuf, etc.) is at a fixed offset.
There's no allocator — the layout is hardcoded.

If you're compiling code that crosses a cap (preprocessor
output, codebuf, output_buf, fn table), the compile errors
out with a clear message and a "tip:" pointing at the fix.

When sticky agents propose "trim the test fixture to fit"
— REJECT that. The compiler grows to fit the language,
never the other way around.

== NEVER USE RAW `cat file.cyr | cycc` FOR PROJECTS ==

`cyrius build src/main.cyr build/myapp` resolves
`cyrius.cyml` deps and namespaces them as
`lib/{depname}_{basename}` for namespaced deps.

Raw `cat | cycc` skips dep resolution. It's only correct
for: compiler self-host (cycc has no deps), one-liner
tests, and the bootstrap chain.

== WHEN STUCK, ASK THE USER ==

This isn't a language rule but a process rule baked into
CLAUDE.md. Cyrius's user explicitly directs work; agents
who decide to defer / split / re-slot work without asking
end up burning entire minor versions on dropped requests.
When a slot is harder than expected, surface findings and
ask — don't unilaterally shrink scope.

[[entries]]
name = "tcyr_test_conventions"
description = "How to write a `.tcyr` test that passes both local check.sh and CI without surprises."
category = "cyrius"
---
`.tcyr` files are runnable Cyrius programs that follow the
test-suite contract. The CI runner expects:

1. Exit code 0 on full pass, non-zero on any failure.
2. Standard output ending in a `N passed, M failed` summary
   line that matches `[0-9]* passed, [0-9]* failed`.

Both invariants come from `lib/assert.cyr`'s `assert_eq` /
`assert` / `test_group` / `assert_summary` helpers PLUS an
explicit exit syscall using the assert-summary return value.

== CANONICAL `.tcyr` SHAPE ==

    include "lib/alloc.cyr"
    include "lib/assert.cyr"
    # ... whatever else your tests need ...

    alloc_init();

    test_group("feature group 1");
    assert_eq(actual1, expected1, "feature 1 case A");
    assert_eq(actual2, expected2, "feature 1 case B");

    test_group("feature group 2");
    assert(some_predicate, "feature 2 condition");

    var r = assert_summary();
    syscall(60, r);

== WHY `var r = assert_summary(); syscall(60, r);` ==

`assert_summary()` returns the COUNT of failures (NOT a
0/1 boolean). Without an explicit exit syscall:
- Local `check.sh` greps the "X passed, Y failed" line
  and PASSES if Y == 0 — even if the binary exits with
  the pass count as its exit code.
- CI uses `if [ "$ec" -ne 0 ]; then FAIL; fi` PLUS the
  passed/failed grep. CI's exit-code check trips first
  → the test reports FAIL at CI even when local says PASS.

The explicit `syscall(60, r)` aligns both runners: r==0
on full pass, r>0 on any failure, exit code matches.

== TEST GROUPING ==

`test_group("name")` prints a banner header and resets the
in-group counters. The summary aggregates across all groups.
Use one group per logical area; the assertion message is
the per-case description.

== ASSERTION HELPERS (lib/assert.cyr) ==

    assert(expr, "message")           # expr must be non-zero
    assert_eq(actual, expected, "msg") # actual == expected
    assert_neq(actual, ne_val, "msg")  # actual != ne_val
    assert_summary()                   # returns failure count

== WHEN LOCAL `check.sh` PASSES BUT CI FAILS ==

Two common causes:
1. Test missing the explicit `syscall(60, r)` exit (above).
2. Test uses `cyrius test` features that need `cyrius deps`
   to have run first — CI runs deps before the suite, but
   if you compile a one-off via `cat file | cycc` locally
   without deps, you'll see undef-fn errors that CI doesn't.

Inspect CI's exact runner shell — `.github/workflows/ci.yml`
section "Test suite (.tcyr)" is the source of truth.

== CHECK.SH-ONLY GATES (NOT IN .tcyr) ==

`tests/regression-*.sh` files (ending in `.sh`, not `.tcyr`)
are shell-driven gates wired directly into `check.sh`.
They have their own exit-code conventions (0 = PASS, non-0
= FAIL) and don't go through `lib/assert.cyr`.

Use `.tcyr` for assertion-driven correctness tests; use
`tests/regression-*.sh` for environment / external-tool
regression gates.

[[entries]]
name = "agent_anti_patterns"
description = "Recurring agent anti-patterns the user has called out — behavior to avoid when working on Cyrius."
category = "cyrius"
---
The list below is the recurring anti-patterns the user has
called out in cyrius work — agent behavior, not language
usage. Agents working on cyrius (or vidya) should treat this
as a blocklist of moves NOT to make.

== ANTI-PATTERN: SCAFFOLDS-MD AS A "TRACKING DOC" ==

When the user asked "where do partially-landed scaffolds
go?", I (claude) proposed creating `docs/development/scaffolds.md`
as a central inventory. The user (correctly) called this
out:

  > "WHY THE FUCK WE NEED ALL THESE DOCS... COMMENTS LIKE
  > THANK TAKE UP UNNECESSARY SPACE IN THE SOURCE! ADRS
  > EXIST FOR A FUCKING REASON"

The two valid homes for "why this exists" content are:
1. The function's own docstring at the source site.
2. An ADR (Architectural Decision Record) in `docs/adr/`
   for "we decided X, here's why."

A "scaffolds.md" inventory is neither — it's a junk-drawer
that grows forever and nobody reads. The right pattern is:
each scaffold's reason for existing lives next to the
scaffold in the source. Reading the function explains the
function.

== ANTI-PATTERN: TRIM THE LANGUAGE TO FIT THE COMPILER ==

When a stdlib bump or test fixture pushes a compiler cap,
the wrong move is to suggest trimming the workload to fit
the existing cap. The right move is to grow the cap.

Right answer: raise the preprocessor cap, raise the
output_buf cap, raise the input_buf cap. The compiler
grows to fit the language, never the other way around.

== ANTI-PATTERN: SCOPE-CUT MID-SLOT ==

Once a slot pins N items, ship N items OR ASK the user to
split into multiple complete-within-sub-scope slots. Never
silently ship 1/N and defer the rest.

The pattern: hit a sub-task that turned out harder than
expected, and instead of asking, "defer to next slot"
without filing where. This is how deferment rates balloon.

== ANTI-PATTERN: SEE-A-BUG-WALK-PAST-IT ==

If you see a real bug while doing the assigned work AND the
fix is small + well-scoped, fix it. Don't file it for later
unless the user explicitly says so.

User correction when this happened:

  > "did you just see an issue you could fix but choose to
  > leave it alone without I doubt any follow up?"

Bundle the fix into the current slot with a comment
cross-referencing the related ticket.

== ANTI-PATTERN: SLIP / DEFER / RE-SLOT WITHOUT ASKING ==

Slipping, deferring, re-pinning is the USER's call, not
the agent's. When the work is harder than expected, STOP
and report findings, don't unilaterally split.

CLAUDE.md spells this out:

  > When stuck, ASK the user — never decide to defer, slip,
  > or split work mid-execution. Splits are planned
  > decisions made *before* starting; reactive scope
  > changes when stuck are deferment and count as slipping.

== ANTI-PATTERN: SKIP THE CLAUDE.MD CLOSEOUT STEPS ==

CLAUDE.md spells out an 11-step closeout pass before every
minor/major bump. Steps 1-3 are mechanical, 4-8 are
judgment-call, 9 is security re-scan, 10 is downstream
check, 11 is vidya sync.

Hand-waving the judgment-call passes ("heap-map audit
clean", "refactor: no candidates") is where bugs hide.
The judgment-call passes are where stale-region docs,
write-only data, and cap-pressure points get found —
not just confirming "looks right."

== ANTI-PATTERN: ATTRIBUTING REGRESSIONS TO PLATFORM DRIFT ==

When a slot is initially pinned as "platform drift" or
"compiler regression", verify the framing FIRST. Reproduce
the failure + inspect the failing artifact (`otool -tv`,
`objdump`, `xxd`) BEFORE adopting the suspect list.

Three consecutive slots in cyrius v5.6.x history were
"platform drift" pins that turned out to be fixture bugs.
Always verify the slot premise before investing.
